{{Use South African English|date=May 2013}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}
{{Apartheid}}

The '''Treason Trial''' was a trial in [[Johannesburg]] in which 156 people, including [[Nelson Mandela]], were arrested in a raid and accused of [[treason]] in South Africa in 1956.

The main trial lasted until 1961, when all of the defendants were found not guilty. During the trials, [[Oliver Tambo]] left the country and was exiled. Whilst in other European and African countries, he started an organisation which helped bring publicity to the [[African National Congress]]'s cause in South Africa. Some of the defendants were later convicted in the [[Rivonia Trial]] in 1964.

[[Albert Lutuli|Chief Luthuli]] has said of the Treason Trial:<blockquote>The treason trial must occupy a special place in South African history. That grim pre-dawn raid, deliberately calculated to strike terror into hesitant minds and impress upon the entire nation the determination of the governing clique to stifle all opposition, made one hundred and fifty-six of us, belonging to all the races of our land, into a group of accused facing one of the most serious charges in any legal system.{{sfn|Joseph|1963|p=14}}</blockquote>

==Background==
On 5 December 1956, the South African Police's Security Branch raided and arrested 140 people from around the country on the charge of treason as they enforced the [[Suppression of Communism Act]].<ref name="NYT05">{{cite news | url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1956/12/06/87278056.html?action=click&contentCollection=Archives&module=LedeAsset&region=ArchiveBody&pgtype=article&pageNumber=1 |url-access=subscription| title=South Africa Seizes 140 in Race Dispute | work=The New York Times | date=6 December 1956 | agency= | accessdate=1 September 2017 | author=}}</ref>{{rp|1,12}} Those not based in Johannesburg were flown there in military aircraft and held in custody until a hearing on 19 December 1956.<ref name=NYT05/>{{rp|12}} The raids were follow-ups to those conducted in 1955 and included search warrants to look for documents at 48 anti-government organisations.<ref name=NYT05/>{{rp|12}}

On the 19 December 1956, 153 prisoners were driven to the Johannesburg Drill Hall for a preliminary hearing to examine the states evidence.<ref name="NYT01">{{cite news | url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1956/12/20/86989181.html?action=click&contentCollection=Archives&module=LedeAsset&region=ArchiveBody&pgtype=article&pageNumber=18 |url-access=subscription| title=AFRICANS' SINGING DROWNS OUT TRIAL | work=The New York Times | date=20 December 1956 | agency= | accessdate=1 September 2017 | author=}}</ref>{{rp|18}} Magistrate Frederick Wessels was the presiding judge with J.C. van Niekerk as the state's public prosecutor.<ref name=NYT01/>{{rp|18}} An attempt by the prosecutor to proceed with the case was interrupted three times as the noise of 5,000 Black South Africans, hoping to attend the case, surrounded the streets of the Drill Hall and sung [[Nkosi Sikeleli Afrika]].<ref name=NYT01/>{{rp|18}} The proceedings had to be halted.<ref name=NYT01/>{{rp|18}} The [[Labour Party (UK)|
Labour Party]] in the UK accused the South African Government of intimidating and victimising those opposed to Apartheid, condemning the trial and called South Africa a police state.<ref name="NYT02">{{cite news | url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1956/12/20/86989181.html?action=click&contentCollection=Archives&module=LedeAsset&region=ArchiveBody&pgtype=article&pageNumber=18 | title=Laborites are critical | work=The New York Times | date=20 December 1956 | agency= |url-access=subscription| accessdate=1 September 2017 | author=}}</ref>{{rp|18}}

Resuming on 20 December 1956, the hearing was interrupted again when the defence objected to their clients being behind a six foot high wire fence.<ref name="NYT04">{{cite news | url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1956/12/21/84947476.html?action=click&contentCollection=Archives&module=LedeAsset&region=ArchiveBody&pgtype=article&pageNumber=9 | title=Police Fire on Mob At Trial in Africa | work=The New York Times | date=21 December 1956 | agency= | accessdate=1 September 2017 | author=|url-access=subscription}}</ref>{{rp|1, 9}} After an adjournment, it was agreed by the two sides to reduce it to a barrier four foot tall.<ref name=NYT04/>{{rp|9}} The prosecutor J.C. van Niekerk then presented an outline of his evidence stretching back to 1953 of the liberation movements activities but his evidence was soon interrupted when violence broke out outside the court.<ref name=NYT04/>{{rp|9}} After police began moving back the crowd of around a 1,000 black protesters, a policeman was injured by a stone and they retaliated by firing into the crowd and surrounding cars and shops, injuring fourteen people. Deputy Police Commissioner Colonel Piet Grobler was able to get his men stop shooting and order was restored.<ref name=NYT04/>{{rp|1,9}}

The trial examination would continue on 21 December 1956 and the prosecutor presented his case as stating that the defendants were subversive, having attended the recent [[Congress of the People (1955)|Congress of the People]] gathering at [[Kliptown]] where speeches had promoted Communism and the creation of the [[Freedom Charter]], the need to seek help abroad and in other evidence, the need to raise money to buy firearms.<ref name="NYT03">{{cite news | url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1956/12/22/84717768.html?action=click&contentCollection=Archives&module=LedeAsset&region=ArchiveBody&pgtype=article&pageNumber=1|url-access=subscription | title=South African Treason Trial Causes New Rioting | work=The New York Times | date=22 December 1956 | agency=Associated Press | accessdate=1 September 2017 | author=}}</ref>{{rp|1, 4}} With no charges yet presented to the individual detainees, bail was granted and the trial was then concluded until 9 January 1957.<ref name=NYT03/>{{rp|4}} Rioting broke out at the end of the days proceedings when police charge a group of 400 Black South African protesters.<ref name=NYT03/>{{rp|4}}

On resumption of the preliminary hearing and an examination of the state's evidence on 9 January 1957, three more defendants were added to the charges bringing the number to 156 persons.<ref name="NYT06">{{cite news | url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1957/01/10/93204794.html?action=click&contentCollection=Archives&module=LedeAsset&region=ArchiveBody&pgtype=article&pageNumber=14 | title=RACIAL PLOT SEEN IN AFRICAN TRIAL | work=The New York Times | date=10 January 1957 | agency= | accessdate=1 September 2017 | author=Hunt, Richard P.|url-access=subscription}}</ref>{{rp|14}} The defence would argue that the Freedom Charter was not treasonous, that it did not call for violence and it argued for peace and racial harmony for the country.<ref name=NYT06/>{{rp|14}}

The hearing was still ongoing during August 1957, the accused were spending six hours each day in court.<ref name="NYT07">{{cite news | url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1957/08/25/95814284.html?action=click&contentCollection=Archives&module=LedeAsset&region=ArchiveBody&pgtype=article&pageNumber=17 | title=TREASON INQUIRY IN AFRICA DRAGS | work=The New York Times | date=25 August 1957 | agency= | accessdate=1 September 2017 | author=Hunt, Richard P.|url-access=subscription}}</ref>{{rp|17}} With the hearing to last a few more months, the magistrate had more 6,200 pages of testimony and 10,000 exhibits to examine and decide whether to pass the sentences himself or let the Attorney General decide whether to proceed to a trial.<ref name=NYT07/>{{rp|17}} The trial was taking so long, the male prisoners formed a choir.<ref name=NYT07/>{{rp|17}}

On 17 December 1957, Attorney General W.J. McKenzie decided to drop charges against 61 and proceed to with the remaining 95 defendants on 13 January 1958.<ref name="NYT08">{{cite news | url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1957/12/18/84985090.html?action=click&contentCollection=Archives&module=LedeAsset&region=ArchiveBody&pgtype=article&pageNumber=15 | title=SOUTH AFRICA FREES 61 IN TREASON CASE | work=The New York Times | date=18 December 1957 | agency=Reuters | accessdate=1 September 2017 | author=}}</ref>{{rp|15}} Albert Luthuli and 44 Black, six Whites, four Indian and six Coloured defendants were released.<ref name=NYT08/>{{rp|15}}

The hearing resumed on 13 January 1958 with the prosecutor informing the court of the names of those 61 defendants who had been cleared of further charges.<ref name="NYT09">{{cite news | url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1958/01/14/89040051.html?action=click&contentCollection=Archives&module=LedeAsset&region=ArchiveBody&pgtype=article&pageNumber=2 | title=TREASON TRIAL RENEWED | work=The New York Times | date=14 January 1958 | agency=Associated Press | accessdate=1 September 2017 | author=|url-access=subscription}}</ref>{{rp|2}}

The hearing concluded on 30 January 1958 with Magistrate F.C. Wessels finding that there was sufficient evidence for the defendants to be tried on charges of high treason.<ref name="NYT10">{{cite news | url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1958/01/31/82207456.html?action=click&contentCollection=Archives&module=LedeAsset&region=ArchiveBody&pgtype=article&pageNumber=1 | title=95 IN SOUTH AFRICA HELD AS TRAITORS| work=The New York Times | date=31 January 1958 | agency= | accessdate=2 September 2017 | author=Hunt, Richard P.|url-access=subscription}}</ref>{{rp|1,3}} The defendants were asked to plead, with all pleading not guilty they were released on bail. Their defence lawyers asked for a jury trial, the alternative being a trial by two or three judges, with the former request being rejected by the state in treason trials.<ref name=NYT10/>{{rp|3}}

The Treason Trial began in Pretoria on 1 August 1958 with 91 people on trial having been charged with high treason.<ref name="NYT11">{{Cite news|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1958/08/02/82212399.html?action=click&contentCollection=Archives&module=LedeAsset&region=ArchiveBody&pgtype=article&pageNumber=4|title=Mass Trial Opens in South Africa|last=|first=|date=2 August 1958|work=The New York Times|access-date=22 September 2018|others=Reuters|url-access=subscription}}</ref>{{rp|4}} The trial saw 57 blacks, 16 whites, 16 Indians and two Coloureds charged with attempting to overthrow the South African government between 1952 and 1956 with the intention to replace it with a communism system.<ref name=NYT11/>{{rp|4}} The defence lawyers opened the trial by lodging an objection to two of the three trial judges. They called for Justice Joseph Ludorf to withdraw because of his involvement as a lawyer in other cases against some defendants while Justice Rans Rumpff should withdraw as he had asked for the former to be appointed as a judge on the treason trial.<ref name=NYT11/>{{rp|4}} The case was then adjourned until the following Monday.<ref name=NYT11/>{{rp|4}}

When the trial resumed on 12 August 1958, chief defence lawyer Israel Maisels continued to challenge the indictment referring to the masses of documentary evidence which he claimed was impossible to read in less than two years, and was a abuse of the court process and that the prosecution did not know what its case was about.<ref name="NYT12">{{Cite news|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1958/08/13/82708280.html?action=click&contentCollection=Archives&module=LedeAsset&region=ArchiveBody&pgtype=article&pageNumber=8|title=Treason Case Scored|last=|first=|date=13 August 1958|work=The New York Times|access-date=22 September 2018|url-access=subscription}}</ref>{{rp|8}}

After the trial collapsed in October, it was decided in November 1958 to resume the trial on 19 January 1959 with a decision to drop 60 people from the indictment.<ref name="NYT13">{{Cite news|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1958/11/14/83423816.html?action=click&contentCollection=Archives&module=LedeAsset&region=ArchiveBody&pgtype=article&pageNumber=8|title=South Africa to Resume Trial|last=|first=|date=14 November 1958|work=The New York Times|access-date=22 September 2018|url-access=subscription}}</ref>{{rp|8}}

On 22 November 1958, 30 of the 91 were re-indicted with the charge now been narrowed down to a conspiracy to endanger and overthrow the state based on the 1955 Congress of the People gathering and the adoption of the Freedom Charter.<ref name="NYT14">{{Cite news|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1958/11/23/110082797.html?action=click&contentCollection=Archives&module=LedeAsset&region=ArchiveBody&pgtype=article&pageNumber=27|title=SOUTH AFRICA OPENS NEW TREASON CASE|last=|first=|date=23 November 1958|work=The New York Times|access-date=22 September 2018|url-access=subscription}}</ref>{{rp|27}} The remaining 61 were to be indicted in April 1959.<ref name=NYT14/>{{rp|27}}

The trial resumed on 19 January 1959 in Pretoria with the defence arguing for the trial to be moved back to Johannesburg, due to the hardship of travel for the defendants, a city where the majority of them lived.<ref name="NYT14B">{{Cite news|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1959/01/20/89108166.html?action=click&contentCollection=Archives&module=LedeAsset&region=ArchiveBody&pgtype=article&pageNumber=8|title=30 IN SOUTH AFRICA ASK VENUE CHANGE|last=|first=|date=20 January 1959|work=The New York Times|access-date=22 September 2018|url-access=subscription}}</ref>{{rp|8}} The case was postponed on the first day until after lunch as the bus carrying the defendants had broken down.<ref name=NYT14B/>{{rp|8}} Trial resumed on 2 February 1959, with the venue change request squashed and the defence lawyers continuing their argument against the new indictments.<ref name="NYT15">{{Cite news|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1959/02/03/89114811.html?action=click&contentCollection=Archives&module=LedeAsset&region=ArchiveBody&pgtype=article&pageNumber=6|title=INDICTMENT ATTACKED|last=|first=|date=3 February 1959|work=The New York Times|access-date=22 September 2018|url-access=subscription}}</ref>{{rp|8}}

With the resumption of the trial on 20 April 1959 of the other 61 defendants, it was ended when Judge R.L. Rumpff declared that the Crown's case could not accuse the defendants of conspiracy without saying how they entered into the conspiracy and that they would need to know in order to defend their case.<ref name=NYT16/>{{rp|4}} The defendants could return home and the prosecution would have to decide whether to re-indict them.<ref name="NYT16">{{Cite news|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1959/04/21/89183556.html?action=click&contentCollection=Archives&module=LedeAsset&region=ArchiveBody&pgtype=article&pageNumber=4|title=SOUTH AFRICA SETS 61 'PLOTTERS' FREE|last=|first=|date=21 April 1959|work=The New York Times|access-date=22 September 2018|url-access=subscription}}</ref>{{rp|4}}

On 29 March 1961, down to 28 defendants, the trial's verdict was released and they were all found not guilty of treason and discharged.<ref name="NYT17">{{Cite news|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1961/03/30/118032375.html?action=click&contentCollection=Archives&module=LedeAsset&region=ArchiveBody&pgtype=article&pageNumber=1|title=28 AFRICANS FREE IN TREASON TRIAL|last=|first=|date=30 March 1961|work=The New York Times|access-date=22 September 2018|url-access=subscription}}</ref>{{rp|1}} Judge F.L.H. Rumpff concluded that the prosecution could not show that the ANC had become a communist organisation and therefore no treason could be proven nor that any act of violence was to be used to overthrow the state.<ref name=NYT17/>{{rp|1}} The defendants were met outside the court by their relatives and saw the singing of Nkosi Sikeleli Afrika.<ref name=NYT17/>{{rp|5}}

== Defendants ==

In December 1956, many key members of the [[Congress Alliance]] were arrested and charged with treason, including  almost the entire executive committee of the ANC, as well as the [[SACP]], the [[South African Indian Congress|SAIC]], and the [[South African Congress of Democrats|COD]]. 105 Africans, 21 Indians, 23 whites and 7 coloured leaders were arrested. Ten were women.{{sfn|Sampson|1958|p=}} Many arrestees, including Nelson Mandela, were detained in communal cells in Johannesburg Prison, known as the Fort, resulting in what Mandela described as "the largest and longest unbanned meeting of the Congress Alliance in years."{{sfn|Mandela|1995|p=149}} However, white men, white women, and black people were all held in a separate parts of the jail.

Initially, 156 defendants were charged with high treason. The number of defendants was later reduced to 92. In November 1957, the prosecution reworded the indictment and proceeded a separate trial against 30 accused. Their trial commenced in August 1959. The remaining 61 accused were tried separately before the case against them was dismissed in mid 1960.{{sfn|Mandela|1995|p=196}}

Treason trial defendants (during various stages of the trial) included:

* Farid Adams (one of the final 30 defendants)
* [[Lionel Bernstein]], known as Rusty, [[Congress of the People (1955)|Congress of the People]] and [[South African Congress of Democrats|Congress of Democrats]]
* Piet Beyleveld
* [[Sonia Bunting]], communist organizer for [[SACP]] and journalist (released in October 1958 after her acquittal)<ref>{{cite web|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=Sonia Beryl Bunting (1922 - 2001)|url=http://www.thepresidency.gov.za/national-orders/recipient/sonia-beryl-bunting-1922-2001|website=The Presidency|publisher=Government of South Africa|accessdate=1 March 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180215031144/http://www.thepresidency.gov.za/national-orders/recipient/sonia-beryl-bunting-1922-2001|archivedate=15 February 2018|location=Pretoria, South Africa|date=2010}}</ref>
* Rev. [[James Calata]]
* [[Yusuf Dadoo]], leader of the [[South African Indian Congress]]
* [[Ruth First]], [[SACP]], journalist and wife of Slovo
* Lionel Forman, lawyer and journalist (indictment withdrawn), died in 1959.
* [[Archie Gumede]], ANC, later leader of the United Democratic Front.
* [[Bertha Gxowa]] (one of the final 30 defendants)
* [[Alfred Hutchinson]] (a [[Coloureds|Coloured]] journalist who fled South Africa before the conclusion of the trial)
* [[Helen Joseph]], white trade unionist and women's leader (one of the final 30 defendants)
* [[Ahmed Kathrada]], accused number three, secretary-general of the Transvaal Indian Youth Congress (one of the final 30 defendants)
* [[Fish Keitseng]]
